    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey so im buying a house in austin and im kinda confused about the earnest money thing. why is it being held in an escrow account instead of just going to the seller? also what happens if the inspection shows something is broken? does the money just sit there? thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Earnest money, a good-faith deposit, is held in escrow because it's a crucial piece of the deal, and you wouldn't want it to just vanish into the seller's pocket before everything is settled. It's like a small, temporary holding pen for the money until the deal is officially closed. If the inspection finds something broken, that money doesn't just sit there; it becomes part of the negotiation, or it might be used to cover repairs if you and the seller agree on a price adjustment. Sometimes, if the inspection reveals a major issue, the earnest money can be used to facilitate a renegotiation or even be returned to you if the contract falls through due to a contingency.",
      "source": "target",
